on jobs, but I now see that UpSnap runs a ping cron job internally for all devices, and the line 137 exit could be related to Ping. Given this, I\u0027m examining how UpSnap handles custom commands via standard Go `exec.Command`, specifically the implications of the `nc -u -w1` wake command and its potential timeout, which would result in an exit 1, and the implications of user set cron jobs. I\u0027ll need to figure out how this is correctly handled, regardless of custom or internal cron job triggers.\n\n\n**Clarifying the Outcome**\n\nI\u0027ve confirmed that the setup functions as intended; the ping command, using `nc -z -w 3`, and subsequent cron jobs with their exit status 1s, correctly represent the device\u0027s state. The wake command, which utilizes `nc -u -w1`, also works as expected, using UDP and resulting in a timeout on the listening end, but the device is awakened as intended. I\u0027m now examining the implications of this design. The ping returns 1 for offline states as desired, which triggers an error log by UpSnap, but is correct behavior.\n\n\n**Modifying the Wake Command**\n\nI\u0027ve got a fix in mind to address the error logging. The wake command successfully sends the packet, but `nc`\u0027s timeout causes a non-zero exit code. Appending `|| true` to the wake command resolves this, ensuring it returns `0` regardless, even if the target is offline. I will evaluate this modification immediately.",
